Barack Obama is the fourth US President to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
U.S. President Barack Obama will visit Oslo, Norway for 26 hours to be the fourth U.S. President in history to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
In addition, he receives the diploma, medal and a cheque worth $1.4 million for his extraordinary efforts to intensify world diplomacy and cooperation among peoples.
The head of the White House arrives tomorrow with his wife Michelle in the northern metropolis and will be busy all the time.
First, he visits the Nobel Institute, where he meets for the first time with the five committee members who elected him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple has scheduled a meeting with Norwegian King Harald V and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit reaches its peak with the ceremony in which Obama takes over the prestige prize.
He is the fourth president of the United States, but only the third to receive the prize directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the war in Afghanistan when he takes over the prize.
The president does not want to evade this issue because he knows that he will take the prize as a president who is currently at war in two countries.
He intensified the war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which none of his critics forget to highlight.
At the ceremony, Obama also received the gold medal, diploma and check of ten million Swedish kronor (approximately 24 million Czech kronor).
He intends to donate the money to charity, but has not yet decided on a concrete charitable work.
The event program then includes a banquet with the President and his wife, with the Prime Minister and another 250 invited guests in addition to Norway’s King and Queen.
Obama was very cautious about the price from the start.
He said, for example, that he feels that he doesn’t deserve the prize.
He also repeated several times that the prize is not only for him, but for all who aspire to the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement, he stated that for him this is "invitation to action".
