USA: Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It is almost weird that Barack Obama, the president with his reputation of the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghanistan issue, which he himself considered the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly anticipated Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it off over the copy paper from the Bush-Iraq scenario three years ago.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, he even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Forward Path" without hesitation.
Three years ago, he himself criticized the Bush idea of sending fresh contingents of troops to Iraq, which was plagued by the civil war, as an "irresponsible and catastrophic decision".
However, the following months showed that the Bush strategy, based on recommendations from the military, was the only one possible and very successful in that today no one talks about Iraq at all in the news.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, for objectively he left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than was to be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will repeat itself.
The military again asked him for an increase in the contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite the subordination habits, harshly criticized the roaring shooters in the White House.
He called for 40,000 soldiers to reverse the situation for the better.
The President delayed for three months, but did not come up with a better idea, and so he cheated the general about 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe, he has pressed the pledge for another 5,000, even though he himself originally expected at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing about the entire Obama strategy is his plan to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 18 months, and to complete this process in three years. The entire Obama doctrine leaves more questions than answers.
Some doubt that the halved increase will have the same effect as the measure in Iraq.
Despite the fraternal war of recent years, the Iraq society is relatively well structured and its leaders honor the values.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the contraindication - no one can be trusted and no agreements are kept.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, who are used to changing their minds every day.
The political institutions, even if they were formally established correctly, remain only fake buildings, behind which the patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
The balancing of interests between the different ethnic groups is unusually complicated, especially because of the obscurity of the situation, which complicates the Pakistan and Iran influences even more.
The construction of a "capable state", which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, is also very unrealistic.
Time horizon of Obama’s strategy alienated by its voluntarism
Over the last eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only further deteriorated and now it is on the verge of explosion.
Believing that the little soldiers who have erupted into the war cry of "early return" can create a miracle here, only a truly romantic soul who is not impressed by facts can.
From a political point of view, the date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, because the Taliban will take it as the indirect confession of the American defeat.
The last NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to participate in the fighting in Afghanistan is fading.
Europe’s politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their voters how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the Hindu Kush mountain range.
Another possible factor that can radically influence the situation is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the increased sanctions do not affect the Iranians, the United States will face a very difficult question of whether the problem cannot be solved with troops.
This question needs to be answered during the time that America moves to Obama’s victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any solution will also mean a dramatic change in the Afghan situation.
The only consolation for Barack Obama is the fact that there are still three years left until the presidential election, and so there is still enough time for him to resort to a different strategy if it turns out to be a total failure.
