Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'steeled' HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works against the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact outweighs the disadvantage that the compound does not act as strongly on conventional virus variants as one of the already existing drugs.
AIDS can’t be cured yet.
However, the patient can prolong life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
Incomplete suppression of virus propagation also leads to the development of resistant viruses against which no drugs are effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, VSCHT (Chemical Technological University) Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have proven that the substances called metalocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the propagation of the HIV virus.
The metalocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in a different way than all drugs used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists come up with new ‘enhanced’ compounds that have been prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the virus protein.
The metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multifaceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms and coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Insidious and persistent virus
HIV protease is the protein of the HIV virus, which is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the cleaving of the HIV virus caused by the HIV protease, no mature infectious virus particles would form.
If we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the propagation of the virus in the patient’s body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the paper published in the scientific journal Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, the scientists describe entire rows of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically further modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in the test tube, also against their resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of the metalocarboranes on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as with the clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on the resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action and its other properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical designs, make metalocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at the development of effective anti-HIV drugs, says Pavlina Rezacova, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
