Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted for a minaret ban and concerns about the alleged Islamization of Europe are widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-thought-out report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe’s declared most secularized societies — and be integrated.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's final work, "Why the French don't love headscarves" (2006), an elegant and densely argumentative study of a dispute that divided and occupied the country over a decade and a half, and whose effects can still be perceived today.
Bowen’s latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what the politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer the 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it, “Islamic free spaces.”
He is a good listener, he reflects debates between teachers and students about the issues that worry them the most.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest rate-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane affairs, he claims, that make up daily life, in contrast to the political dramas that the media are dealing with.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen on the other in a modern secular society.
They don’t have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists that Bowen interviewed are mostly in disagreement with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of purist Sunni Islam associated with Saudi Arabia – who nowadays show a small but influential presence among Europe’s Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions to what extent French policymakers (and the intellectual elite so passionately guarding the separation of church and state) are truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historic compromise with secular republicanism.
He recognizes a "sharpening of the value screws" rather than a growing pragmatism.
After reading this book, one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
