The Arctic is changing faster and more dramatically than any other environmental region on Earth.
The ice that characterizes them melts at an alarming rate, taking lives that nowhere else can survive.
Oil, gas, shipping and fishing interests have gone into the newly open waters, with diplomats, lawyers and now also authors in their keel waters.
Richard Ellis, an author and illustrator, draws in "On Thin Ice" (original title: "On Thin Ice") a natural history of the icon of the North, the polar bear.
Known in the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who have proven themselves in hunting polar bears.
Admiral Nelson’s encounter with a polar bear as a brave 14-year-old sailor who fought only with his musket’s rifle butterfly is certainly a legend, but others are true.
Young bears caught swimming behind the bodies of their recently killed mothers were taken to zoos and circuses.
A circus performance at the beginning of the 20th century showed 75 polar bears at a performance.
Even today, zoos typically still own one-millionth of the wildlife area of an ancient animal. The climate is rarely suitable: The polar bear in Singapore became quite green from the algae that grow in the hollow hairs of his fur.
