Ellis refers to the accounts of other authors and historians and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, America and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where hunters in helicopters and motor sleigh-driving Inuit use powerful assault rifles to track down their prey.
Ironically, in the waters in the north of these two hunting nations, the ice will last the longest.
In his new book, After the Ice, Alun Anderson, a former editor of the science magazine New Scientist, offers a clear and disturbing description of the science of the Arctic and a gripping insight into how the future could evolve.
Not that scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of the changes.
This is not due to a lack of explanations.
The pioneering journeys of Fridtjof Nansen at the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th century for the first time suggested the turbulence of the pack ice.
In the Cold War, submarines saw the moving ridges while underwater.
A useful addition are satellite surveys and the large-area deployment of probes on icebergs, but still much is achieved by intrepid people camping outside in the cold.
Anderson takes a look at the peculiar, tiny world of the inflow system within the Arctic ice formed by saltwater cascades compressed during freezing.
But, from the bear on the ice to the microscopic wonders in the ice, everyone is threatened by the passing of the summer ice, which is expected in the period between 2013 and 2050.
