"Shanghai will soon be as old -- but not as rich -- as the industrialized countries, like Japan and Sweden," she said.
A step-by-step relaxation
Enshrined in the country’s 1978 constitution, China’s one-child policy is arguably the most controversial provision introduced by the ruling Communist Party to date.
Married couples who violate this policy face huge fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination in their workplace.
Chinese officials have attributed to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of policy.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who already had a child to aborte.
Many couples also had sex-selective abortions, which resulted in an unnaturally high ratio of men to women.
In recent years, government officials for the population have gradually weakened their attitude to one-child policies.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife have been single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many harsh slogans was mitigated.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at the Institute of Population Research at the University of Beijing, said government officials have recently discussed even more radical changes, for example, allowing couples to have two children with a partner who is an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters teaching families to have only one child have been replaced almost overnight by guidelines describing in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent city employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and push through information sheets under the doors.
She also asked for psychological and financial advice for those who have more than one child.
The response was not exactly encouraging, family planning officials said.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outskirts of Shanghai said that there was an upswing in the applications from couples who wanted a second child after the campaign started, the urban districts, on the other hand, reported no change.
The Huinan municipality with a population of 115,000 still receives as an example only four to five applications per month.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that the expected number of births in the city for 2010 will still be around 165,000 despite the campaign -- slightly higher than 2009, but lower than 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Caolu Community Family Planning Committee in Shanghai, said financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don’t want to have more children.
They want to give their first one the best, she said.
Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that this is legally permitted.
But they, like many Chinese, have only a small government health and life insurance.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge the one-child policy as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is seven months pregnant with her first child.
Yes, we are robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
The problem is not simply in politics.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the human resources manager, said she only wants a child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to the fact that everyone took care of us.
We’re not used to caring for others and we don’t really want to.”
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with double careers, which lowers the birth rate, he said, it’s about being successful and for that you have to be selfish.
The age group of today’s 20- to 39-year-olds grew up watching their parents fight during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they don’t want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, puts huge demands on parents’ time.
A mother must give up her social life for at least two years.
Then there's the room question -- "You have to rebuild your apartment" -- and life planning -- "When the child is 9 months old, you already have to have a resume ready for the best preschools."
Most of his friends are ready to go through this once, Chen said, but not twice.
Our generation is the first to achieve a higher standard of living, he said.
We do not want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group Drafts Plan to Reduce Emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which so far has been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has once again set a focus on Friday with the release of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases for the next 40 years, with industrialized nations having to bear the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement on greenhouse gas control, has both identified the remaining obstacles and shown the way forward.
But it was seen as important progress in a negotiation that is running out of time, as more than 100 top politicians from around the world will arrive in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent on the money supply that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can manage global warming in the short and long term.
It also offers a range of options for key issues, including how industrialized and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and what the upper limit of global temperature rise should be that policymakers would support.
The process is given a great deal of flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the UN’s leading climate protection official, Yvo de Boer, has called “the big picture.”
It shows the outline of a possible agreement whereby developed nations would collectively reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 thresholds, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent over the same period.
Together, the countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community also boosted Friday’s talks by pledging to allocate $3.6 billion a year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impacts of climate change – from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
U.S. Climate Special Representative Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for mandatory reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for developed countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies if they are not funded by the developed nations.
This train announced that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line with China than Bush administration representatives not even two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging markets standing up and taking action, Stern said, complaining that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the cuts could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern made his statement an hour after China’s Deputy Secretary of State He Yafei stated that the leading American climate negotiator was either lacking “reason” or it was “highly irresponsible” by him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not help China financially to cope with global warming.
With the future economic march of the great world powers at stake, lines of fracture have arisen both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle equally relates to saving individual economies, as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their corresponding commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take more courageous action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it is not surprising that the major powers are struggling to determine who should bear the costs of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have moved to take more aggressive measures to hold countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic hegemony will develop, says Ulate, who is also working as a regional climate change advisor for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the impacts of climate change said they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leading participants say the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of Small Island States with 43 members presented a 24-page draft treaty early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said the offensive of the small island states "exerts political pressure on the entire political process," partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging economies, such as China and India.
The talks were given a new urgency as the delegates focused on the fact that most of the open issues still need to be clarified before the arrival of the leaders to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as India’s Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and China’s Deputy Minister, got off their planes and raced through the corridors of the Bella Center to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to identify claims to be negotiated over the next week.
The pure scale of the gathering -- 13,000 people go in and out of the convention center every day, guitar-playing activists host night-time shows making fun of the countries they think are betraying and selling, and draft contracts are hand-in-hand rather than emailed -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: Almost all major ministers are now here and from Wednesday, 60 government leaders will be in Copenhagen.
“We’re coming to the upper league,” said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President of Global Policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
