The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would have been nothing special.
However, Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these body features, Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science reported Thursday.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window on the early evolution of the dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He tells us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for Triassic deposits, team member Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History reports.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
Find confirms theories about dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually you only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of the dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current teaching, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primitive dinosaurs is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three main developmental lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, which are known as "long necks".
According to Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found clues to airbags, as they also possess the descendants of the theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with airbags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of giant sauropods later also had airbags and lightweight bones, probably the common ancestor of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America to all continents, which at that time still formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangaea.
This is supported by the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, it could be a distorted picture, because in South America, especially many primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved, while there is hardly anything to be found on other continents.
How the dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile tribe to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Earth’s Middle Ages is still mysterious.
During the Triassic, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example, with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and fly-saurs, and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread around the world, developing many new species, while the kinship at the border of the Triassic to the Jura became extinct.
Success story didn’t last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals bloom, which had also evolved in the Triassic, and since then a shadow existed: the mammals.
