About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, people can no longer distinguish between the inner and the outer world, they fall into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, size, relationship or persecution.
Particularly common is hearing voices - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also not uncommon.
The affected person is no longer able to separate the important from the unimportant, the brain is no longer able to filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded by impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis also opens the doors to a flood of ideas and fantasies that originate from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician at the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of the action, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is, like in a dream, overwhelmed by the events and cannot actively shape them.
