Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of astonishingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraines, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer’s and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, even the brain of healthy people hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Box, are composed of memory contents that are usually held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or insufficiently inhibited; when our brain is hot or also when there is no stimulation.
Drugs can trigger this condition just as much as brain damage or psychosis.
But also stimulus withdrawal, stress, love distress or other mental exceptional states.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having had a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005 Sarah K. is 16 years old, she lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attends high school there.
A normal girl, actually.
If it weren’t for pictures and voices.
During the break, it may happen that a sloppy boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it responds to him, the classmates look at it with surprise - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think of the shy girl as a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows that.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bench next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for a moment.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other delusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening
Often the misconceptions are also a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material because the teacher in her eyes and ears is just introducing a new classmate, while he explains mathematical equations to everyone else, both audible and visible on the board.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which is far too rare and far too late, she can often not distinguish whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees, the scraps or the girl with the bleeding cut wounds on her arms and legs, arise in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her about it, they'd think she was crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated from high school last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Since she made contact with the psychologist Box on the Internet, she knows exactly that she is not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art from despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from stimulus withdrawal, they are most likely to have hallucinations after a while, Kasten says.
I suspect that the brain is then underemployed and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., a single child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at age 13 that the man she has been calling Dad since she can think is not her biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations have the same brain regions that process real impressions and sounds, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between fantasies and reality.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why they seem so real.”
Even night dream images value box as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their misconceptions as irreal.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to appreciate the hallucinations as a special ability.
The boundary between dream and hallucination
In our too much-conscious world, imaginary experience is unfortunately mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy of the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also carries positive, creative – madness is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oniroid form of experience, a special form of traumatically altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the waking state even afterwards.
The oniroid state of consciousness arises in extreme trauma or disease-related situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis when fully conscious.
When a person is threatened with loss of self and the world, for example by sustained, complete inability to move, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own, imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of boundary state between dream and hallucination.
Since coping with a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is present in the imagination.
An intensive form of meaning creation and meaning in an intrinsically unbearable situation that allows us humans our own ability to design, not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oniroid experiences in his book "Changing Hearts" as a rescue of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body is sentenced to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immerses himself in a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot guards his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make intoxicants from blood.
When a Greek rides a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
It is completely absorbed in the imagined event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is another state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travels are clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience blows the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says the psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
In the end, oniroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug addiction show how fragile our inner images of external reality are also in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, the psychologist sums up box, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
