75% of working mothers have problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the conclusion of the study "Fertility and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in collaboration with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women between the ages of 15 and 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market limited because of their maternity.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and the number of children, depending on whether the women work or not and, if so, what kind of profession they practice.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only half-day or do not have a fixed employment contract are more likely to become mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with a permanent job, especially in the public sector, move the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"The women in the age group between 35 and 49 years with a permanent employment get their first child on average only 3.7 years after moving together, a number that increases to 4.1 years for women with a permanent employment who have taken longer to achieve this and who have moved together and the first child realized much later.
Moreover, the type of work also has a major impact on maternity, albeit less than the calendar in terms of willingness to conceive," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that needs to be taken into account in the age of the women at the time of marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference was also found in women of the same age.
For example, the women in the group between the ages of 35 and 49, depending on whether they have only high school or higher education, were on average mothers for the first time with 25.1 or 32.1 each.
Furthermore, depending on their level of education, there is another difference between women.
While the women with a major degree get married before their first permanent job and have their first child, the women with a middle or high school graduation do the other way around and first look for a permanent job and then marry and then have their first child, notes Delgado.
