Assistance in braking in critical situations is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is now the case with the ESP stability control system, the assistive braking systems for emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, for the remaining vehicles a deadline was set until the end of February 2011.
The measure adopted by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many collisions due to their operation.
The task of the emergency braking assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver, which detects the system on the brake pedal based on the braking strength implemented by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one-third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even step on the brake pedal before the collision and half of them had not braked at full power.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, acts with maximum force into the braking system and thereby reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car covers during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented each year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency braking assistance.
There would be even fewer accidents - one in four accidents could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or a camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
When the driver responds, the system helps to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assistant applies maximum pressure to the brakes in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
