Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed to the workshops, where an expert must assess the damage and repair costs.
Not a single accident is the same and calculating the cost of the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including parts and hours of work, can take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools, it is a matter of minutes.
That is why almost 100% of reviewers use this type of system.
Accident assessment and repair service and application providers collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process it thereafter and offer it to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all expert opinions are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing with in the tool market for reviewing and drafting a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, it works with 63 manufacturers and importers, each of whom provides the information in a different format.
In addition, the amount of data to be processed is increasing, to the point that more versions, variants and motorizations have been released on the market in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes on the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is an arduous task, because each of the thousands of vehicle parts must be catagolized and its price entered.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" on different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week, if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If it is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Currently, Audatex has complete information for 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not about Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the vehicle fleet on the roads, it is over 99%.
For the purpose of performing the documentation work and producing databases, Audatex has eight centers distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
There, more than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) work simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>90 million annually in the development of these databases.
They record 2.5 million data every month and their customers receive the updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use it in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the file or residual value of a car.
The only company that has a guide that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products Audatex offers, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it gives to the industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of the products being AudaPlus, a standard solution for assessing accidents for evaluators.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles and light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the cost of the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid for depending on the intended use, i.e. for each expert report.
It will be the most expensive for customers who rarely use it, a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5.75 euros per month.
On the other hand, any insurance company that produces thousands of expert opinions negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment it used to run from the assembly line using the chassis number alone.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle panes, and AudaSubastas is an internet service open to the specialist market, which can be used to provide vehicles that have been declared to be totally damaged.
Your statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, performing geodemographic analyses or obtaining information about deviations by brand and model.
For example, it can be used to investigate how many models of a particular car brand had to enter the workshop due to breakdowns or how many of them were involved in a serious accident in a certain period of time.
Gt Motive is the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes, among other things, Gt Estimate, which is also intended for reviewers and provides digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer in the same way.
Gt Motive is a company of the Einsa Group, which was founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, breakdowns and maintenance of vehicles.
The GT guide for expert opinions is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 reviewers and 53 insurance companies.
Their business volume has increased by 20% annually in the last three years and sales in 2008 amounted to 10.8 million euros.
At the beginning of last year, they started to enter the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company’s sources, 62% of its business is in Europe and the rest of the world, and the remaining 38% in North and South America. They work with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
Total revenue in the world of the Solera Group (Audatex, Sidexa, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounts to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenues of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the group Solera was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange and today its shares are traded at a value of 2.4 billion dollars.
